    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1506435237,
    "creation_date" : 1506435237,
    "answer_id" : 46428835,
    "question_id" : 542979,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you are not using \"-XX:HeapDumpPath\" option then in case of JBoss EAP/As by default the heap dump file will be generated in \"JBOSS_HOME/bin\" directory.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 21692212,
      "reputation" : 25,
      "user_id" : 16006682,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GjQssP75LZFIPoiahJrIo3SCFL89LZnZdAHerMsKw=k-s256",
      "display_name" : "Aashish Patil",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/16006682/aashish-patil"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1625752282,
    "creation_date" : 1625752282,
    "answer_id" : 68302971,
    "question_id" : 542979,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you only configure -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError parameter then heapdump will be generated in JBOSS_HOME/bin directory for OpenJDK/Oracle JDK. If you are using IBM JDK then heapdump will be created under /tmp directory as phd file. -XX:HeapDumpPath option gives us more feasibility for configuring our custom headpump path location (-XX:HeapDumpPath=/my-custom-jboss-server-path/). It's recommended to have this parameters configured in your environment as it will collect heapdump on OutOfMemory error for analyzing the issue with memory leak of the application or checking any large object retention in the application.</p>\n"
  } ],
